\tilde x^1 &= r\\
\tilde x^2 &= \phi\\
\tilde x^3 &= z\\
\end{align}
where $(r,\phi)$ are plane polar coordinates in the $(x,y)$ plane. 
Now I thought that this would be rather easy to calculate when we use that
\begin{align}
ds^2 = g_{ij} \, dx^i \, dx^j = -dt^2 + dx^2 + dy^2 + dz ^2.
